00:35:12.090 --> 00:35:13.490
will help you get started.

00:35:13.490 --> 00:35:16.080
So with that, let's get rolling.

00:35:16.080 --> 00:35:18.310
Building a team is not very
different from building

00:35:18.310 --> 00:35:18.880
a product.

00:35:18.880 --> 00:35:21.430
You have to start with
a thoughtful intention.

00:35:21.430 --> 00:35:23.170
What kind of team do I want?

00:35:23.170 --> 00:35:25.020
What do I want my
team to achieve?

00:35:25.020 --> 00:35:27.610
And when it comes to
building VR design teams,

00:35:27.610 --> 00:35:31.185
we often struggle with these
basic fundamental questions.

00:35:31.185 --> 00:35:34.330
Partially, because a
lot of us are new to VR.

00:35:34.330 --> 00:35:36.630
But primarily because
designing for VR

00:35:36.630 --> 00:35:40.650
is significantly different from
designing for other mediums.

00:35:40.650 --> 00:35:43.680
Unlike web or mobile, where
we used to spend a lot of time

00:35:43.680 --> 00:35:46.370
designing flat
UIs, for VR we have

00:35:46.370 --> 00:35:49.160
to design a world with
environments, lights,

00:35:49.160 --> 00:35:51.950
and sound, shadows, and motion.

00:35:51.950 --> 00:35:55.760
UI is just one a
component of that world.

00:35:55.760 --> 00:35:58.650
Designing this world
requires new design skills,

00:35:58.650 --> 00:35:59.440
different tools.

00:35:59.440 --> 00:36:00.870
It needs more time.

00:36:00.870 --> 00:36:03.760
And then we have to adapt
our processes and workflows

00:36:03.760 --> 00:36:06.540
as a technology rapidly evolves.

00:36:06.540 --> 00:36:09.890
All the factors combined
demand a VR design team

00:36:09.890 --> 00:36:12.670
that's different and unique,

00:36:12.670 --> 00:36:16.220
Well successful VR design teams
have three unique attributes.

00:36:16.220 --> 00:36:20.000
Number one, designers
wear multiple hats.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:24.020
No one in such teams is just
an interaction designer or just

00:36:24.020 --> 00:36:25.470
a 3D artist.

00:36:25.470 --> 00:36:27.530
Instead you will find
an interaction designer

00:36:27.530 --> 00:36:30.270
who is also good at
3D, or a prototyper

00:36:30.270 --> 00:36:32.590
but who has a keen
eye for motion.

00:36:32.590 --> 00:36:34.880
Personally as a
designer, even though it

00:36:34.880 --> 00:36:37.670
might sound intimidating,
wearing multiple hats

00:36:37.670 --> 00:36:42.090
is what makes designing
for VR so much fun.

00:36:42.090 --> 00:36:45.260
Then VR design teams a
highly collaborative.

00:36:45.260 --> 00:36:47.890
Every advancement
in VR technology

00:36:47.890 --> 00:36:50.010
is opening doors to
endless possibilities

00:36:50.010 --> 00:36:53.210
of new interactions
and experiences.

00:36:53.210 --> 00:36:57.060
And the only way to explore
them at speed and scale

00:36:57.060 --> 00:37:00.630
is to work together, by sharing
and learning from each other.

00:37:00.630 --> 00:37:03.100
And as Rob mentioned
earlier, his team

00:37:03.100 --> 00:37:06.370
explored new ideas every
week by working together

00:37:06.370 --> 00:37:08.560
in small teams,
focusing on the problem,

00:37:08.560 --> 00:37:11.250
and then sharing their learnings
with the rest of the team

00:37:11.250 --> 00:37:13.900
in their demo parties.

00:37:13.900 --> 00:37:16.430
And finally, successful
VR design teams,

00:37:16.430 --> 00:37:19.010
even though they celebrate
diversity amongst their team

00:37:19.010 --> 00:37:23.070
members, they somehow
don't let the roles

00:37:23.070 --> 00:37:25.690
get in the way of
getting things done.

00:37:25.690 --> 00:37:28.070
It's very rare to hear
that, I don't this.

00:37:28.070 --> 00:37:29.940
This is someone else's job.

00:37:29.940 --> 00:37:33.050
Designers are very willing to
get out of their comfort zone

00:37:33.050 --> 00:37:35.300
and take on new challenges.

00:37:35.300 --> 00:37:37.710
But what are these skills
that I'm talking about?

00:37:37.710 --> 00:37:41.390
What kind of skills are actually
needed in a VR design team?

00:37:41.390 --> 00:37:45.280
A VR design team
requires diverse skills.

00:37:45.280 --> 00:37:48.370
And depending on the product
that you are building,

00:37:48.370 --> 00:37:50.430
these skills might
change a little bit.

00:37:50.430 --> 00:37:52.870
But typically a
design team, which

00:37:52.870 --> 00:37:56.760
is building VR interfaces,
require these skills.

00:37:56.760 --> 00:37:58.970
Now a word of caution,
some of these skills

00:37:58.970 --> 00:38:01.750
might look very familiar,
but the applications

00:38:01.750 --> 00:38:02.980
are quite different.

00:38:02.980 --> 00:38:05.590
For example, while
designing interactions,

00:38:05.590 --> 00:38:08.520
one has to additionally
consider spatial organization

00:38:08.520 --> 00:38:10.980
and hierarchy and
use game engines

00:38:10.980 --> 00:38:12.680
to create volumetric layouts.

00:38:12.680 --> 00:38:15.960
For visual design, the
concepts of grid and typography

00:38:15.960 --> 00:38:20.000
completely change as things are
layered in different z-depths.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:22.090
Now I do understand
that, if you're

00:38:22.090 --> 00:38:24.060
starting to build
a new team, this

00:38:24.060 --> 00:38:26.520
might seem like a lot
of skills to find.

00:38:26.520 --> 00:38:29.080
So in that case, I would
suggest you to start

00:38:29.080 --> 00:38:30.520
with at least two designers.

00:38:30.520 --> 00:38:34.010
This will help them collaborate,
bounce ideas off of each other,

00:38:34.010 --> 00:38:36.960
providing each other feedback
and solve problem faster

00:38:36.960 --> 00:38:39.304
when one of them gets stuck.

00:38:39.304 --> 00:38:40.970
Between these designers,
you should have

00:38:40.970 --> 00:38:43.020
at least these three skills.

00:38:43.020 --> 00:38:45.760
If you recall the process
diagram that Michael shared,

00:38:45.760 --> 00:38:49.170
3D design prototyping
and interaction design

00:38:49.170 --> 00:38:50.920
were the fundamental skills.

00:38:50.920 --> 00:38:52.950
And frankly, you
can't accomplish much

00:38:52.950 --> 00:38:55.350
without these
fundamental skills.

00:38:55.350 --> 00:38:58.410
Other skills can be included at
different phases of the project

00:38:58.410 --> 00:39:00.510
as the need arises.

00:39:00.510 --> 00:39:02.650
Now you might be
wondering where are

00:39:02.650 --> 00:39:05.730
these are designers who
have multiple skills

00:39:05.730 --> 00:39:07.900
and could juggle
with different hats.

00:39:07.900 --> 00:39:09.304
Well, they're around you.

00:39:09.304 --> 00:39:11.720
There's a good chance that you
might find a designer who's

00:39:11.720 --> 00:39:16.430
already designing VR experiences
and has these multiple skills.

00:39:16.430 --> 00:39:18.270
If that happens, that's awesome.

00:39:18.270 --> 00:39:20.580
But if it doesn't, then
you have to branch out

00:39:20.580 --> 00:39:24.150
and look our and scout
other design industries.

00:39:24.150 --> 00:39:26.870
We have noticed that
designers building games

00:39:26.870 --> 00:39:28.470
have great previous skills.

00:39:28.470 --> 00:39:31.390
They also have the experience
of finding creative solutions

00:39:31.390 --> 00:39:34.410
to the strict performance
requirements of VR.

00:39:34.410 --> 00:39:37.680
VFX designers are awesome
at making things feel larger

00:39:37.680 --> 00:39:38.830
than life.

00:39:38.830 --> 00:39:41.450
If they have experience
with realtime graphics

00:39:41.450 --> 00:39:44.030
and some exposure
to VR, they can be

00:39:44.030 --> 00:39:47.460
of great value for your team.

00:39:47.460 --> 00:39:49.580
For designers from
web and mobile,

00:39:49.580 --> 00:39:51.660
designing information
and creating

00:39:51.660 --> 00:39:54.790
fine and meaningful interaction
is their bread and butter.

00:39:54.790 --> 00:39:58.000
If they additionally have
3D skills or VR prototyping

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:00.840
skills, they can be great
assets for your team.

00:40:00.840 --> 00:40:03.230
And don't forget,
there are a lot

00:40:03.230 --> 00:40:06.480
of students who are working on
VR projects and design programs

00:40:06.480 --> 00:40:08.140
across the world.

00:40:08.140 --> 00:40:10.060
A thorough VR project
done at school

00:40:10.060 --> 00:40:13.220
can give a student
enough domain experience

00:40:13.220 --> 00:40:15.200
to start working
on a real product.

00:40:15.200 --> 00:40:18.140
So if you can guide
them, they can be

00:40:18.140 --> 00:40:20.820
a great addition to your team.

00:40:20.820 --> 00:40:22.590
But these are all industries.

00:40:22.590 --> 00:40:25.690
Where do you actually go
to find these designers?

00:40:25.690 --> 00:40:29.340
Well, I would say start with
maker events like game jams

00:40:29.340 --> 00:40:30.250
and VR jams.

00:40:30.250 --> 00:40:33.020
There is nothing better
than seeing the designers

00:40:33.020 --> 00:40:34.202
in their element.

00:40:34.202 --> 00:40:35.910
And if you get a chance
to jam with them,

00:40:35.910 --> 00:40:37.490
work with them on an idea.

00:40:37.490 --> 00:40:42.370
You can think of it like
speed dating in certain ways.

00:40:42.370 --> 00:40:45.120
In this process, you
will learn a lot more

00:40:45.120 --> 00:40:47.290
about these designers
than you will ever

00:40:47.290 --> 00:40:50.000
learn through regular
formal interviews.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:52.930
There is also a good chance
that you can find such talent

00:40:52.930 --> 00:40:56.550
at conferences like this one
and other tech events that

00:40:56.550 --> 00:40:59.300
happen all around the globe.

00:40:59.300 --> 00:41:01.200
The fact that you're
here, all of you,

00:41:01.200 --> 00:41:05.070
means that you share a common
passion and common interest.

00:41:05.070 --> 00:41:07.870
And who knows, someone sitting
under this geodesic dome

00:41:07.870 --> 00:41:10.840
could be a future colleague.

00:41:10.840 --> 00:41:14.570
And lastly, social media can
be surprisingly effective.

00:41:14.570 --> 00:41:17.480
But you need to go beyond
the obvious mediums.

00:41:17.480 --> 00:41:22.770
Imagine watching someone on
YouTube who is passionately

00:41:22.770 --> 00:41:24.660
presenting their VR demos.

00:41:24.660 --> 00:41:27.330
Or Twitch, a lot
of designers have

00:41:27.330 --> 00:41:29.480
started using Twitch
to live broadcast

00:41:29.480 --> 00:41:30.860
their creative process.

00:41:30.860 --> 00:41:33.200
Watching a designer walk
you through their process

00:41:33.200 --> 00:41:35.960
of creating beautiful
VR environments,

00:41:35.960 --> 00:41:38.170
it will not only inform
you about the subject,

00:41:38.170 --> 00:41:41.720
but will also help you find a
great designer for your team.

00:41:41.720 --> 00:41:43.950
And of course,
following people's work

00:41:43.950 --> 00:41:46.380
and honest opinions
on Reddit and Twitter

00:41:46.380 --> 00:41:49.850
can definitely reveal a lot
about their passion and domain

00:41:49.850 --> 00:41:51.580
knowledge.

00:41:51.580 --> 00:41:56.000
So for those of you who
are building design teams,

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:59.140
here are some tips of
finding promising candidates.

00:41:59.140 --> 00:42:00.570
And those of you
who are designers

00:42:00.570 --> 00:42:03.940
who want to join this team,
this is a good example

00:42:03.940 --> 00:42:06.570
of what these design leaders
would be looking for.

00:42:06.570 --> 00:42:08.910
So as a design
leader, you would come

00:42:08.910 --> 00:42:11.390
across stunning portfolios,
beautiful renderings,

00:42:11.390 --> 00:42:13.040
and impressive language.

00:42:13.040 --> 00:42:14.480
And all that is important.

00:42:14.480 --> 00:42:17.510
But you will additionally need
to look for a few other things.

00:42:17.510 --> 00:42:22.390
One, has the person
made anything in VR?

00:42:22.390 --> 00:42:25.370
And I'm not talking about
a major project or years

00:42:25.370 --> 00:42:26.970
of industry experience.

00:42:26.970 --> 00:42:28.830
I'm talking about are
they tinkering in VR?

00:42:28.830 --> 00:42:31.640
Are making fun little small
demos in their free time

00:42:31.640 --> 00:42:33.170
after their day job?

00:42:33.170 --> 00:42:34.300
This is very important.

00:42:34.300 --> 00:42:39.090
Because if the answer is
no, then for a designer,

00:42:39.090 --> 00:42:41.260
learning new tools and
working with new technology

00:42:41.260 --> 00:42:43.150
can be very stressful.

00:42:43.150 --> 00:42:50.210
And even as the team leader, it
will become difficult for you

00:42:50.210 --> 00:42:55.790
to be helpful in transitioning
this designer as a VR designer.

00:42:55.790 --> 00:42:58.850
And then diverse skill
sets, we have already

00:42:58.850 --> 00:43:01.950
talked about the importance of
having multiple design skills,

00:43:01.950 --> 00:43:05.980
as a designer can wear multiple
hats when the need arises.

00:43:05.980 --> 00:43:09.800
And it requires true
passion to continue

00:43:09.800 --> 00:43:12.390
learning new things every
day and taking initiatives

00:43:12.390 --> 00:43:14.760
to explore new possibilities
that are created.

00:43:14.760 --> 00:43:17.160
Now, if you find a
designer with these skills,

00:43:17.160 --> 00:43:21.730
I'll say act fast
and be flexible.

00:43:21.730 --> 00:43:25.240
And in a few days from now, if
you forget everything I said,

00:43:25.240 --> 00:43:27.250
just remember these four things.

00:43:27.250 --> 00:43:31.130
Build a culture where skills
are valued more than roles.

00:43:31.130 --> 00:43:34.300
Build a culture which
encourages teams to share

00:43:34.300 --> 00:43:36.010
and learn from each other.

00:43:36.010 --> 00:43:37.910
Keep an open mind
for fresh talent,

00:43:37.910 --> 00:43:40.000
and you will be
pleasantly surprised.

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:44.040
And cast a wide net so
that you can get new talent

00:43:44.040 --> 00:43:46.700
and build a more diverse team.

00:43:46.700 --> 00:43:48.530
And then, for some
reason, if you

00:43:48.530 --> 00:43:50.730
don't want to build
a full blown team,

00:43:50.730 --> 00:43:53.122
then consider involving
a design studio.

00:43:53.122 --> 00:43:55.330
There are several design
studios across the world who

00:43:55.330 --> 00:43:56.935
are making great VR content.

00:43:56.935 --> 00:43:58.560
And if you want to
know more about this

00:43:58.560 --> 00:44:01.080
you can find me after this talk.

00:44:01.080 --> 00:44:03.270
And I really hope that
this information helps

00:44:03.270 --> 00:44:06.000
you answer the question that we
